abstract: New York Times reporters followed the exchanges and provided context around the candidates’ claims.
snippet: New York Times reporters followed the exchanges and provided context around the candidates’ claims.
lead_paragraph: Ten candidates vying for the 2020 Democratic presidential nomination took the stage on Thursday in Miami for the second of back-to-back debate nights. The 10 other candidates who qualified for the debates appeared on the same stage on Wednesday.

headline_main: Fact-Checking Night 2 of the 2020 Democratic Debates

abstract: Tonight is part two of the first Democratic debate. Join Lisa Lerer and other Times reporters as they chat about what’s happening onstage.
snippet: Tonight is part two of the first Democratic debate. Join Lisa Lerer and other Times reporters as they chat about what’s happening onstage.
lead_paragraph: Welcome to a special debate night edition of On Politics. I’m Lisa Lerer, your host.

headline_main: Analysis of Night 2 of the June Democratic Debates

abstract: Kamala Harris stood out from the 10-person crowd several times during the NBC debate. Her exchange with Joe Biden, who is leading in the polls, put him on the defensive.

abstract: The network simulcast the Democratic debate in Spanish, and had interpreters prepare for months to be able to translate “Medicare for all” in real time.
snippet: The network simulcast the Democratic debate in Spanish, and had interpreters prepare for months to be able to translate “Medicare for all” in real time.
lead_paragraph: On the crowded debate stage, two presidential hopefuls offered up answers in Spanish — however imperfect — early in the evening.

abstract: It wasn’t always feathers, floats and celebrities.
snippet: It wasn’t always feathers, floats and celebrities.
lead_paragraph: When we hear of Pride marches today, we tend to think of fuss and feathers, of men more than half-naked waving from rainbow-hued, Lurex-draped parade floats, of Dykes on Bikes who gun their motors in defiance of gender norms, of waving gay and trans celebrities. They are fiestas that percolate through the cities and sometimes small towns of the developed world, as well as some parts of the rest of the world, and they mark the fact that gay people exist in numbers, provide documentary evidence that we have more fun and are more fabulous than anyone else, that we are gay in the old sense of the word. The drag queens and gender-nonbinary youth at such events can appear preoccupied with their own ecstatic exhibitionism.
